article.description:
Jennie Lillis had 16 points, nine rebounds and three blocks,
leading Iowa to an 81-61 victory over Minnesota on Thursday night.
article.headline: Faulkner scores 22 points for Hawkeyes
article.linkText: Iowa upsets Minnesota, eyes NCAA tourney
article.story:
IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) -- Iowa hit Minnesota with something that
caught the Gophers (No. 12 ESPN/USA Today, No. 11 AP) off-guard: aggressive defense from
end to end.

Known more for its offense, Iowa harassed Minnesota with
full-court pressure and half-court traps and rolled to an 81-61
victory Thursday night behind 22 points from Kristi Faulkner.

"I really think they threw the first punch and I don't know if
we were completely prepared for that, that they were going to bring
that sort of defense," Minnesota's Kadidja Andersson said.

Iowa (15-9, 9-4 Big Ten) kept its NCAA tournament hopes alive
with one of its most complete games of the season. The Hawkeyes
shot 50 percent, forced 23 turnovers and were never threatened
after taking an early 12-point lead.

"This was a big win for us. We really want to get to the (NCAA)
tournament," said Iowa's Jennie Lillis, who had 16 points, nine
rebounds and three blocks. "I think we came out with a different
defensive tenacity tonight. It fed the whole way through."

Minnesota (19-5, 8-5) played its second full game without
leading scorer Lindsay Whalen, who'll be sidelined four to six
weeks with a broken right hand. The Gophers won at Illinois without
her Sunday, but she was missed in this one.

Whalen had scored 28 points in a 75-61 victory over Iowa in
Minneapolis last month. Without her, the Gophers struggled to get
open shots and handle the ball.

"You can pressure Minnesota more now," Iowa coach Lisa Bluder
said. "With Lindsay, it seemed like she was always bailing them
out. Tonight, they didn't have anybody to bail them out."

Janel McCarville led Minnesota with 12 points, but the Gophers
needed more than that from their 6-foot-2 center. McCarville picked
up two quick fouls, got her fourth with 14:39 left and fouled out
with 10:20 to go.

Faulkner drew a charge against McCarville for the fourth foul
and drew the fifth on a jump shot. Jamie Broback added 10 points
for the Gophers. Jamie Cavey scored 15 for Iowa.

"They really came out with their guns firing," Minnesota coach
Pam Borton said. "They kind of put us back on our heels right from
the beginning, kind of broke everything down offensively that we
were trying to run."

Iowa could play aggressively on defense because Minnesota had no
one who could beat a defender off the dribble, one of Whalen's
strengths.

Minnesota made only two field goals in the first 8:47 and turned
the ball over nine times as Iowa jumped to a 19-7 lead. Reserve
Crystal Smith sparked the defense with three steals, the last of
which she took in for a layup.

The Hawkeyes made four 3-pointers in stretching the lead to
35-13, and Tiffany Reedy's spinning jump shot made it 40-18 late in
the first half. Minnesota drew to 40-22 at halftime and cut the
lead to 42-27 early in the second half on Shannon Bolden's layup
but got no closer.

Lillis hit a 3 from the left wing and Cavey got behind the
defense for a layup to return the lead to 20. Any chance Minnesota
had of making a run ended when McCarville fouled out and Iowa went
on to lead by as many as 25.

"We set the tone early instead of fighting back," Bluder said.
"We've had to fight back from a lot of deficits this year. This
one, we took control early. I think that gave us a lot of
confidence."
